{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480692"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"95"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"95","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/95"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.02,0.5,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"95"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77084"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"95","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/95"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"95"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62590"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"149"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37155"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77084"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with an unwitnessed fall. She has a five-month history of recurrent falls, progressive gait disturbance, and urinary incontinence. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears confused. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She is disorientated to time and has difficulty maintaining attention during conversation. She has a broad-based, slow, magnetic gait.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most preferred investigation for establishing the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT brain","BGL","MRI brain","ECG","EEG"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of normal pressure hydrocephalus (NPH): gait disturbance, cognitive decline, and urinary incontinence. The characteristic magnetic gait, confusion, and progressive symptoms over months make this diagnosis likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred investigation for NPH. It can demonstrate the characteristic ventriculomegaly and also helps exclude other pathologies that can present similarly. MRI provides superior detail of brain tissue and CSF spaces compared to CT, allowing better assessment of the extent of hydrocephalus and any underlying causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT brain\u003C/strong\u003E is often performed first due to availability and to exclude acute pathology such as subdural haematoma, it is less specific than MRI for establishing the diagnosis of NPH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EBGL\u003C/strong\u003E (blood glucose level) should be checked as part of the initial workup of confusion, but would not help establish the diagnosis of NPH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if a cardiac cause for falls was suspected, but the progressive nature of symptoms and characteristic triad make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEEG\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if seizures were suspected, which is not suggested by the clinical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming the diagnosis with MRI, patients may undergo additional testing such as large-volume CSF removal (tap test) to assess their likelihood of responding to CSF shunting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal pressure hydrocephalus classically presents with the triad of gait disturbance, cognitive decline, and urinary incontinence.","MRI is the preferred imaging investigation for normal pressure hydrocephalus as it better demonstrates ventriculomegaly and can exclude other pathologies.","Initial cognitive assessment and exclusion of reversible causes is essential in patients presenting with falls and confusion."],"references":["Nassar BR, Lippa CF. Idiopathic Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus: A Review for General Practitioners. Geront Ger Med 2016; 2:1-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28138494/","Bradley WG Jr. Magnetic Resonance Imaging of Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus. Semin Ultrasound CT MR. 2016 Apr;37(2):120-8. doi: 10.1053/j.sult.2016.01.005. Epub 2016 Jan 20. PMID: 27063662.","Damasceno BP. Normal pressure hydrocephalus: Diagnostic and predictive evaluationon. Dement Neuropsychol. 2009 Jan-Mar;3(1):8-15. doi: 10.1590/S1980-57642009DN30100003. PMID: 29213603; PMCID: PMC5619025."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62590"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"95"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62590"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T08:54:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T11:41:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"95"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionR